INFLUENZA, CANINE - USA (04): (TEXAS) HISTORICAL CONTEXT
********************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 2 Oct 2011
From: David M Morens <dm270q@nih.gov> [edited]


Canine influenza seems not to be a new disease but to have been around
for probably a century or more. See a couple of recent articles on
this: Morens DM, Taubenberger JK: Historical thoughts on influenza
viral ecosystems, or behold a pale horse, dead dogs, failing fowl, and
sick swine. Influenza Other Respi Viruses 2010; 4(6): 327-37
[available at
http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.1750-2659.2010.00148.x/full],
and Morens DM, Taubenberger JK: Pandemic influenza: certain
uncertainties. Rev Med Virol 2011; doi: 10.1002/rmv.689. (Epub ahead
of print) [abstract available at
http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/rmv.689/abstract].

While it is true that we can say canine influenza was not proven to
exist before the virology era, when viruses began to be isolated, that
can also be said about human and equine influenza too. But most ID
historians think the exhaustively documented clinical and
epidemiologic evidence compiled over centuries makes it unlikely that
all the epidemics/pandemics were anything other than the exact same
disease we see today. In particular there are many independent
documentations of horse to dog transmission during equine epizootics
of what to all intents and purposes seemed then, as now, to be
influenza, as well as occasional evidence of transmission between
humans and dogs. Over a century ago influenza, transmitted from horses
to dogs, was seen in racing greyhounds. While we can of course be
conservative and say there is no evidence that any of these diseases
were influenza, it is also possible to consider all of this old
influenza activity as clues to how influenza evolves and is
maintained.

--
David M Morens, MD
Senior Advisor to the Director
